## Executive Overview

NEREUS-H1 represents a next-generation biomimetic underwater exosystem designed to extend human aquatic mobility while maintaining physiological safety, modularity, energy efficiency, and environmental responsibility.

Unlike conventional scuba systems that rely on:

• Open-circuit compressed gas tanks
• Passive fins
• Petroleum-based neoprene suits
• Limited propulsion systems
• Manual buoyancy management

NEREUS-H1 integrates:

• Semi-rigid pressure-resistant exoshell architecture
• Closed-loop breathing systems
• Hydrogen-electric hybrid power
• Whale-inspired biomimetic propulsion
• AI-assisted buoyancy and life support
• Modular S/M/L anthropometric adaptation

The architecture was designed to maximize:

• Endurance
• Maneuverability
• Operator safety
• Environmental sustainability
• Future scalability


## 1. Development Objectives

### Enable Fish-Like Human Mobility

Create efficient cetacean-inspired propulsion to provide natural underwater locomotion.

### Eliminate Continuous Gas Venting

Closed-loop gas recycling minimizes wasted breathing gas.

### Maximize Safety Redundancy

Multiple fail-safe layers ensure survivability under single-point failures.

### Reduce Environmental Impact

Lower material toxicity and improve repairability and recyclability.

### Establish Modular Manufacturing

Develop S/M/L platforms with high component commonality.


